visuals.description: Positive electrons and ions are all constantly traveling along the magnetic field lines of our earth. Auroras are created when these particles are combined with the gas atoms in the upper atmosphere at high speed and an amount of light is given off. The earths magnetosphere is created when the protons and electrons from the suns magnetic field burn off of it. This is called "Solar Wind". Solar wind pushes on the earths magnetic field and this compression is referred to as the magnetosphere. This compression also gives the auroras their shape and causes them to move in the ways that they do.
visuals.instructions: Drag the mouse to the bottom of the screen and let the solar wind lines start to rise. Once you see a black background try pressing the keys "C" "V" "B" "N" and "M" . Have fun!

visuals.description:
Based on https://www.openprocessing.org/sketch/377231.

TIP: While experimenting with the idea of the above sketch, I discovered something valuable that could be useful to anyone using the Processing IDE (this does NOT apply to p5 or Processing.js): calling rect(x, y, 1, 1) with no stroke is dramatically faster than ellipse(x, y, 1, 1) and point(x, y). visuals.title: Maze Generator: Randomized Kruskal's Algorithm
visuals.description:
Another maze generation program. This is one is a lot less fun than the last one but the code is a lot tidier and there is now a working solver. 

For more resources on Kruskal's algorithm, see:
* http://weblog.jamisbuck.org/2011/1/3/maze-generation-kruskal-s-algorithm
* https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maze_generation_algorithm#Randomized_Kruskal's_algorithm
Basically, it puts the cells into sets, which are all merged (by removing a wall between them) until all the cells are connected. The colors you see are the sets.

Kruskal's algorithm generates perfect mazes with a uniform spanning tree.
